<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12046l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12046l">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12046l"> 46(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ gui caught in white apron / golden sickle / when on tree god in</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Pline l&apos;Ancien nous montre aussi les druides pr&eacute;sidant &agrave; des rites moins cruels <font color="green">[fn: Hist. Nat., XVI, 249 sqq.]</font>. &ldquo;Les druides, raconte-t-il, ne connaissent rien de plus sacr&eacute; que le gui et que l&apos;arbre sur lequel il pousse, &agrave; condition que ce soit un ch&ecirc;ne. C&apos;est dans les bois de ch&ecirc;nes qu&apos;ils ont leurs sanctuaires et ils n&apos;accomplissent aucun rite sacr&eacute; sans feuilles de ch&ecirc;nes. Ils croient que l&apos;apparition du gui r&eacute;v&egrave;le la pr&eacute;sence du dieu sur l&apos;arbre qui le porte. Quand ils en ont d&eacute;couvert sur un ch&ecirc;ne, ils le cueillent en grande c&eacute;r&eacute;monie. Ils choisissent de pr&eacute;f&eacute;rence le sixi&egrave;me jour de la lune, parce que ce jour-l&agrave; l&apos;astre poss&egrave;de, pensent-ils, toute sa vigueur et n&apos;a pas encore accompli la moiti&eacute; de sa course. Ils font sous l&apos;arbre sacr&eacute; les pr&eacute;paratifs d&apos;un banquet et d&apos;un sacrifice; ils am&egrave;nent aupr&egrave;s de lui deux taureaux blancs dont les cornes sont vierges du joug. Un pr&ecirc;tre v&ecirc;tu d&apos;une robe blanche monte sur l&apos;arbre: il coupe, avec une faucille d&apos;or, le gui que l&apos;on recueille dans un drap blanc. Les druides immolent enfin les victimes en demandant &agrave; la divinit&eacute; que le gui porte bonheur &agrave; ceux &agrave; qui elle l&apos;a donn&eacute;. <br> <font color="green">[Pliny the older shows us also that the druids presided at less cruel rites [fn: Hist. Nat., XVI, 249 sqq.]</font>. &ldquo;The druids&rdquo;, he narrates, &ldquo;did not hold anything more sacred than the mistletoe and the tree on which it grew, at least if it was an oak. It was in the oak woods that they had their sanctuaries and they did not do their sacred rites without oak leaves. They believed that <mark>the appearance of the mistletoe reveals the presence of the god of the tree on which it grows</mark>. When they found it on an oak, they cut it with great ceremonies. They chose the sixth day of the moon because they believed that on that day the star possesses all its vigour and it has not completed half of its journey. Under the sacred tree they prepare a banquet and a sacrifice; they bring two white steers whose horns have not yet carried a yoke. <mark>A priest in a white robe climbs the tree: with a golden sickle he cuts it</mark> and the mistletoe is caught in a white sheet. The druids then kill the victims while asking the god that the mistletoe may bring happiness to all to whom he has given it.&rdquo;] <small> Albert Grenier, <a name="AGLG" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AGLG"><cite title="source">Les Gaulois</cite></a> (1923) 125</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>gui</i>: mistletoe.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c12033g" href="c12all.htm#c12033g">VI.C.12:033(g)</a></mm></dd> </dd></dl>
